To answer these questions, we need to divide the total number of cereal bits by the total number of designs. So, 63 cereal bits divided by 9 designs gives us 7 cereal bits per design. This suggests that she may not have used an equal number of cereal bits in each design as there are 2 designs left without any cereal bits (i.e., some designs had more than others).

Here is the Python code to calculate it:

```python
total_cereal_bits = 63
total_designs = 9

cereal_bits_per_design = total_cereal_bits / total_designs
print(f"Cereal bits per design: {cereal_bits_per_design}")
```

Running this code would give you: `Cereal bits per design: 7`.
